# RESTful API Conventions

## Response Format (always use Handler)

```php
return $this->handler->successResponse($data, true, $message, 200);
return $this->handler->errorResponse(false, $message, null, 404);
```

```json
{ "success": true, "message": "...", "data": {} }
```

Never use raw `response()->json()` in controllers.

## REST Routes

| Action | Method | URI | Code |
|--------|--------|-----|------|
| index | GET | `/entities` | 200 |
| show | GET | `/entities/{id}` | 200 |
| store | POST | `/entities` | 201 |
| update | PUT/PATCH | `/entities/{id}` | 200 |
| destroy | DELETE | `/entities/{id}` | 200 |

- URIs: kebab-case plural (`/service-providers`)
- Routes in `routes/Api/{Entity}.php`
- Prefer REST over action URLs (`POST /foods` not `/add-food`)

## Thin Controller Template

```php
public function store(StoreFoodRequest $request) {
    $food = $this->foodService->store($request->validated());
    return $this->handler->successResponse(
        ['food' => new FoodResource($food)],
        true, $this->message('food_created'), 201
    );
}
```

- Validate with FormRequest
- Transform with Resource / Resource::collection
- Localize messages via `Accept-Language` header
- Extract pagination meta to avoid duplication

## Auth Middleware

- `auth:api` — client & provider
- `auth:owner` — admin
- `auth.provider.or.owner` — provider or admin
